<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12005i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12005i">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12005i"> 5(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 3 K / soldiers of S. Corn&eacute;ly / be chased turns them / to stone</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> nous nous trouvons ici en pr&eacute;sence d&apos;une croyance singuli&egrave;re et tr&egrave;s int&eacute;ressante, qui lie leur origine &agrave; la punition des gens coupables d&apos;impi&eacute;t&eacute;. / Les menhirs de Carnac, par exemple, qui, au bord de la mer, dans l&apos;impressionnante m&eacute;lancolie d&apos;une lande sauvage, profilent sur plus de <mark>trois kilom&egrave;tres</mark> de longueur leurs magnifiques avenues, pourquoi les appelle-t-on <mark>Soldats de saint Corn&eacute;ly</mark>? Parce que le saint &eacute;v&ecirc;que poursuivi un jour et <mark>chass&eacute;</mark> vers l&apos;Oc&eacute;an par une arm&eacute;e de Boches, de pa&iuml;ens veux-je dire, ne vit d&apos;autres moyens de leur &eacute;chapper <mark>que de les changer en pierres</mark>. <br><font color="green">[&hellip; we find ourselves in the presence of a unique and very interesting belief that ties their origin to the punishment of the impious. / Why, for example, do we give the name &lsquo;Soldiers of Saint Corn&eacute;ly&rsquo; to the menhirs of Carnac, which, on the seashore, in the awe-inspiring melancholy of a savage land, trace their magnificent avenues for more than three kilometres? Because the sainted bishop one day was followed by a Boche &mdash; I mean pagan &mdash; army, and was chased towards the ocean. He saw no way other of escaping them than turning them to stone.]</font> <small> l'Abb&eacute; A. Millon, <a name="AMPB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMPB"><cite title="source">Pauvres Pierres! Les Megalithes Bretons devant la science</cite></a> (n.d) 16</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
